{% extends "parts/base" %}
{% block title %}
	QuickStart
{% endblock %}
{% block content %}

<p>You want to try our compiler? LibFirm in itself is just a library, so you probably want our C frontend cparser. Here is the fastest way to get it running.
</p><p><b>We assume a 32bit Linux or OSX environment here</b>
</p><p>Check it out with git:
</p>
<pre>git clone <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/git/cparser/">http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/git/cparser/</a>
cd cparser
</pre>
<p>If you want the latest release, instead of the developement version, checkout the latest tag.
</p><p>Additionally, we need the libFirm library, which is included as a submodule.
</p>
<pre>git submodule update --init
</pre>
<p>Now build everything. You need a C compiler, GNU Make, Perl, and Python.
</p>
<pre>make
</pre>
<p>You probably have a multicore machine? Then use something like <tt>make -j4</tt> for a parallel build.
</p><p>Now you should have a working binary.
</p>
<pre>build/cparser --version
</pre>
<p>Our compiler tries to be a drop in replacement for GCC, so it supports the same arguments.
Try it on some C99 code, like <tt>cparser -Wall -O3 test.c</tt> or <tt>make CC=cparser</tt>.
</p><p>If you find bugs, please report them in our <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~firm/bugs/">issue tracker</a>.
</p>
{% endblock %}
